# In-code documentation

In-code documentation means **comments that explain what the code alone cannot make obvious**. Good code is mostly self-explanatory; comments fill gaps the reader cannot infer from names and structure alone.

## When to comment

Add a comment when at least one applies:

| Situation | What to document |
|-----------|------------------|
| **New or changed type role** | Class-level responsibility block — [stomp4j-class-responsibilities.mdc](stomp4j-class-responsibilities.mdc). |
| **STOMP spec detail** | Normative behaviour, version differences (1.0 vs 1.1 vs 1.2), header semantics, frame layout edge cases — cite spec section or command (e.g. `CONNECT` heart-beat negotiation). |
| **Architecture decision** | Why this module/layer owns the logic, transport vs protocol boundary, thread model, why an internal package is used. |
| **Rejected alternative** | Another approach considered and **why it was not chosen** (performance, spec violation, broker quirk, JPMS boundary). |
| **Non-obvious invariant** | Ordering requirements, idempotency, lifecycle rules aligned with [domain-specification.md](../../docs/domain-specification.md). |
| **Intentional deviation** | Documented broker quirk or known gap; point to ARCHITECTURE.md §13 when user-visible. |
| **Test or fix rationale** | After a non-trivial test fix, briefly state why production vs test was changed (see [stomp4j-test-failure-diagnosis.mdc](stomp4j-test-failure-diagnosis.mdc)). |

## When not to comment

- Restating what the code already says (`// increment counter` above `count++`).
- Narrating every step of a straight-line method.
- Duplicating Javadoc that only repeats parameter names.
- Large tutorials — use [docs/](../../docs/) or ARCHITECTURE.md instead.

## Style

- Prefer **block comments** above the relevant statement or small block; use line comments only for a single trailing clarification.
- Keep comments **short and factual** — one to four sentences unless a spec citation needs a bit more.
- Use domain terms: `Destination`, `Subscription`, `Frame`, `Session`, `Transport`.
- Link spec by name/version in prose; full URLs belong in markdown docs, not in every comment.

## Examples

```java
// STOMP 1.2: heart-beat header is "cx,cy" in CONNECT; server may answer with adjusted values in CONNECTED.
// We send 0,0 when the client did not request beats — spec allows disabling outbound heart-beats.
negotiateHeartBeats(connectHeaders);
```

```java
// Artemis expects WebSocket subprotocol v12.stomp on port 61614, not the OpenWire port (61616).
// Using 61614 matches broker.xml in test resources and StompActiveMqContainer.
```

```java
// Not using a second parse pass: MessageBuffer must decode incrementally from the transport
// read loop; buffering full frames would break heart-beat octet interleaving on TCP.
```

```java
// Rejected: fire-and-forget SUBSCRIBE without waiting for broker receipt — races with SEND
// in integration tests and violates our settleSubscription invariant before publish.
awaitSubscriptionReceipt(subscription);
```

## After protocol or boundary changes

- New non-obvious STOMP behaviour → comment at the decision point **and** update [domain-specification.md](../../docs/domain-specification.md) if vocabulary or invariants change.
- User-visible gap or quirk → ARCHITECTURE.md §13 in the same change.

